  <tr> 
    <td class="text"><!-- #BeginEditable "caption" -->This cluster of baked clay balls is an obvious example of the use of baked clay as a substitute for cooking stones. When heated,  grapefruit-sized &quot;balls&quot; of wet clay  were transformed into  crude  ceramic objects that could hold and slowly release  heat for baking, just like heated pieces of sandstone and limestone. Similar artifacts have been found at many sites along the Gulf coastal plains where stone is hard to find. The same function is attributed to &quot;Poverty Point Objects&quot; (shaped pieces of baked clay) found at the famous Poverty Point site (ca. 1500-800 B.C.) in Louisiana. TARL Archives. <!-- #EndEditable --></td>
